 environmental hazards of the time are also taken into account, the labour contribution of children becomes even more remarkable. Using a variety of archival materials, the author has conducted a study that gives readers a fuller understanding of how families survived, how the wheat economy was developed, and how burdens were carried on the shoulders of the smallest farm labourers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChild laborzPrairie ProvincesxHistory. 0aFarm lifezPrairie Provinces. 0aFrontier and pioneer lifezPrairie Provinces. 0aPioneer childrenxEmploymentzPrairie Provinces. 0aPioneer childrenzPrairie ProvincesxSocial conditions. 0aRural familieszPrairie ProvincesxSocial conditions. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh  aPrairie History / Labour History / Family Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088864793140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780888647931423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780888647931/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles